{{Primary sources|date=August 2008}} {{Infobox video game |image=Gradius ReBirth Coverart.png |developer=[[M2 (game developer)|M2]] |publisher=[[Konami]] |director=Masato Misaki |programmer=Hiroshi Yoneyama |composer=[[Manabu Namiki]] |series=''[[Gradius]]'' |platforms=[[WiiWare]] |released={{vgrelease|JP|September 2, 2008|NA|March 9, 2009|PAL|July 3, 2009}} |genre=[[Scrolling shooter]] |modes=[[Single-player video game|Single-player]] }}
{{nihongo|'''''Gradius ReBirth'''''|グラディウス ReBirth|''Guradiusu Ribāsu''}} is a [[shoot 'em up]] [[video game]] for [[WiiWare]] developed by [[M2 (game developer)|M2]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtwo.co.jp/|title=有限会社エムツー |website=Mtwo.co.jp |date= |accessdate=2016-08-17}}</ref> and published by [[Konami]]. It is the latest installment in the [[Gradius]] series, and was released in Japan on September 2, 2008,<ref name=www>{{cite news|last=McFerran|first=Damien|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2008/08/gradius_rebirth_hitting_japan_next_week|title=Gradius ReBirth Hitting Japan Next Week|website=[[Nintendo Life]]|date=2008-08-29|accessdate=2018-01-14}}</ref> and in North America on March 9, 2009, and in the PAL regions on July 3, 2009.<ref>{{cite news|last=McFerran|first=Damien|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2009/03/usa_wiiware_update_gradius_rebirth|title=USA WiiWare Update: Gradius Rebirth|website=Nintendo Life|date=2009-03-09|accessdate=2018-01-14}}</ref>
==Gameplay== ''Gradius ReBirth'' is a side-scrolling 2D shooter much like previous ''Gradius'' games, and has been described as a "remix" of levels from past games rather than an entirely new game. The game features two modes: a standard game with unlimited credits and a Score Attack mode where players are only given a single credit to beat the game. Score Attack also supports online leaderboards.<ref name=impressions>{{cite news|last=Bazin|first=Robert|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2008/09/first_impressions_gradius_rebirth|title=First Impressions: Gradius Rebirth|website=Nintendo Life|date=2008-09-03|accessdate=2018-01-14}}</ref> The game features five different types of ships to choose from, and five stages in total, with each (except the first stage) having its own original [[Boss (video gaming)|boss]] at the end.
==Plot== This game takes place in the Gradian Year 6664, two years before "The Silent Nightmare Incident". The planet Antichthon, a protectorate of the Gradian Empire, suddenly and mysteriously falls silent. A report was made by the Director General of the Space Science Agency, Dr. Venom, which mentions that Antichthon's mother computer was now under the control of the Bacterians.
Realizing that a threat from the Bacterians may be imminent, the Gradian Government deploys its Gradian forces to combat the threat. Among them is Special Colonel James Burton, who had defeated the Bacterians a few years ago. Armed with an A.I. program called Gaudie, James Burton sets out in the hyperspace fighter known as the Vic Viper, in the hopes that he can combat the new Bacterian threat. But little does James know that there's much more in store for him...
==Development== ''Gradius ReBirth'' uses the ''Nemesis'' titles for the [[MSX]] as its basis. The power meter and text display have also been updated. The music was composed by [[Manabu Namiki]] and consists of remixed music from previous ''Gradius'' games.
An update to the game was released on the Wii Shop Channel for free of charge. It improves some of the visuals and adds a new ranking board for the adjustments made to the score system. In addition to this, there are new music tracks and a few changes to the game's levels.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.jp/products/dl_wii_gradius_re_ww/index.html|title=GRADIUS ReBirth|website=Konami.jp|date=2014-03-26|accessdate=2018-01-14}}</ref>
==Reception== {{Video game reviews | MC = 69/100<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/wii/gradius-rebirth |title=Gradius ReBirth for Wii Review |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2018-01-14}}</ref> | GRadar = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/gradius-rebirth-review/|title=Gradius ReBirth review|website=[[GamesRadar+]]|first=Tom|last=McShane|date=2009-08-14|accessdate=2018-01-14}}</ref> }}
''Gradius ReBirth'' garnered positive reviews. [[IGN]] gave the game 7/10, praising the nostalgic retro design but finding the game to be punishingly hard for most players and the lack of multiplayer disappointing.<ref>{{cite web|first=Daemon|last=Hatfield|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2009/03/10/gradius-rebirth-review|title=Gradius ReBirth Review|website=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[News Corporation]]|date=2009-03-09|accessdate=2018-01-14}}</ref> Despite also praising the retro visuals and soundtrack, NintendoLife gave ''Gradius ReBirth'' 6/10.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/reviews/2009/03/gradius_rebirth|title=Gradius ReBirth Review|last=Dillard|first=Corbie|website=Nintendo Life|date=2009-03-10|accessdate=2018-01-14}}</ref>
