{{Unreferenced|date=September 2018}} The term "nursery rhyme" emerged in the third decade of the nineteenth century although this type of children's literature previously existed with different names such as ''Tommy Thumb Songs'' and ''Mother Goose Songs''.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Twinkle, Twinkle, Southern Cross: The Forgotten Folklore of Australian Nursery Rhymes|last=Holden|first=Robert|publisher=National Library Australia|year=1992|isbn=064210560X|location=Canberra|pages=1}}</ref> The very first known book containing a collection of these texts was ''[[Tommy Thumb's Pretty Song Book]]'', which was written by M. Cooper and was published in 1744.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Uncle John's Endlessly Engrossing Bathroom Reader|last=Bathroom Readers' Institute|first=|publisher=Simon and Schuster|year=2011|isbn=9781607104599|location=New York|pages=}}</ref> The works of several scholars and collectors helped document and preserve these [[Oral tradition|oral traditions]] as well as their histories. These include [[Iona and Peter Opie]], [[Joseph Ritson]], [[James Halliwell-Phillipps|James Orchard Halliwell]], and [[Walter Scott|Sir Walter Scott]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=From the Garden to the Street: Three Hundred Years of Poetry for Children|last=Styles|first=Morag|publisher=Cassell|year=1997|isbn=0304332240|location=London|pages=84}}</ref>
