{{About||the fifty-fifth Venetian doge|Marino Faliero|the opera by Donizetti|Marino Faliero (opera)}} {{EngvarB|date=September 2013}} {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}} {{Infobox play | name = Marino Faliero, Doge of Venice | image = Marino Faliero 1821.jpg | image_size = 150px | image_alt = | caption = First edition title page | writer = [[Lord Byron]] | chorus = | characters = {{plainlist| *[[Marino Faliero]] *Bertuccio Faliero *Lioni *Benintende *Michel Steno *Israel Bertuccio *[[Filippo Calendario|Philip Calendaro]] *Dagolino *Bertram *Signor of the Night *First Citizen *Second Citizen *Third Citizen *Vincenzo *Pietro *Battista *Secretary of the [[Council of Ten]] *Angiolina *Marianna }} | mute = | setting = [[Venice]] | premiere = {{Start date|df=yes|1821|04|25}} | place = [[Theatre Royal, Drury Lane|Drury Lane]], London | orig_lang = English | series = | subject = The downfall of Marino Faliero | genre = Historical tragedy | web = }} '''''Marino Faliero, Doge of Venice''''' is a blank verse tragedy in five acts by [[Lord Byron]], published and first performed in 1821.
== Synopsis ==
The play is set in [[Venice]] in 1355. [[Marino Faliero]], recently elected [[Doge of Venice]], offends one of the chief officers of state, Michel Steno. Steno retaliates by writing on the Doge's throne an indecent libel on Faliero's wife. For this he is tried by the [[Council of the Forty|Council of Forty]] and convicted, but is only sentenced to a month's imprisonment. Faliero is so outraged by this, as he believes, inadequate punishment that he secretly joins in the conspiracy of a group of malcontents to overthrow the constitution of Venice, thinking thereby to gain revenge on his enemies. The plot is discovered and Faliero is executed.
== Composition and publication ==
Byron was inspired to take on this subject when, on examining the portraits of the Doges in the [[Doge's Palace, Venice|Palazzo Ducale]] in Venice, he discovered that the portrait of Faliero had been blacked out.{{sfn|Plant|2002|p=91}} The main historical source he drew on was [[Marino Sanuto the Younger|Marino Sanuto]]'s ''Vite dei Doge'' (published posthumously 1733).{{sfn|Marchand|1977|p=131}}{{sfn|Marchand|1978|p=161}} He completed the play in July 1820, by which time he was living in [[Ravenna]], and published it in April 1821, along with his ''The Prophecy of Dante''.{{sfn|Quennell|1990|p=596}}{{sfn|Marchand|1978|pp=66–69}} He intended to dedicate it to [[Johann Wolfgang von Goethe|Goethe]], but delays in the post between Italy and England resulted in the play being published without a dedication.{{sfn|Marchand|1977|p=206}} The posthumous 1832 edition of Byron's collected works included a later dedication of the play by Byron to his friend [[Douglas Kinnaird]].{{sfn|Marchand|1978|p=195}} ''Marino Faliero'' was translated into French in 1830 and into Italian in 1838.{{sfn|Plant|2002|p=91}}
== First performance ==
Byron intended his play to be read rather than acted, and when he heard that the actor-manager [[Robert William Elliston]] intended to stage it he caused his publisher, [[John Murray (1778–1843)|John Murray]], to obtain an injunction to prevent him. Elliston nevertheless performed it, in a version cut almost by half, at [[Drury Lane]] four days after the play was published. The reaction from both audiences and critics was lukewarm; perhaps, as Byron thought, because of the play's [[Neoclassicism|neoclassical]] form and lack of sensationalism and love interest.{{sfn|Quennell|1990|p=653}}{{sfn|Smith|2005|pp=139–41}}{{sfn|Marchand|1978|p=66}}
== Influence == [[File:Eugène Delacroix - The Execution of Doge Marino Faliero - WGA06168.jpg|thumb|upright|''The Execution of the Doge Marino Faliero'' ([[Eugène Delacroix|Delacroix]], 1825–26)]]
The subject of [[Eugène Delacroix]]' painting ''The Execution of the Doge Marino Faliero'' (1825–26), now in the [[Wallace Collection]] in London, was suggested by Byron's play.{{sfn|Duffy|2004|p=240}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oxfordartonline.com/subscriber/article/grove/art/T021888?q=byron+faliero+delacroix&search=quick&pos=1&_start=1#firsthit |title=Delacroix, (Ferdinand-)Eugène(-Victor) |author=Harrison, Colin |work=Grove Art Online |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref> A tragedy by [[Casimir Delavigne]] on the same subject is believed to have drawn on Byron, as well as on a story by [[E. T. A. Hoffmann]], and Delavigne's play itself inspired [[Gaetano Donizetti|Donizetti]]'s opera ''[[Marino Faliero (opera)|Marino Faliero]]''.{{sfn|Plant|2002|p=91}} [[Algernon Charles Swinburne|Swinburne]] was impelled to write his own ''Marino Faliero'' by what he considered shortcomings in Byron's play.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bartleby.com/223/0510.html |title=The Rossettis, William Morris, Swinburne, and Others. § 10. Tristram of Lyonesse |author1=Ward, A. W. |author2=Waller, A. R. |lastauthoramp=yes |work=The Cambridge History of English and American Literature in 18 Volumes |publisher=Bartleby.com |accessdate=22 July 2012}}</ref>
== Notes == {{reflist|30em}}
